04155nam a22005415i 9780804772532DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202009cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047725327 a10.1515/97808047725322doi  a(DE-B1597)563967  a(OCoLC)1198929118  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHD6971.8b.H49 2010eb 7aPOL0290002bisacsh04a331.22221 aHeymann, Jody, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRaising the Global Floor :bDismantling the Myth That We Can't Afford Good Working Conditions for Everyone /cJody Heymann, Alison Earle. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. The Struggle Below the Surface: Declining Working Conditions -- t2. The Argument that Humane Working Conditions Lead to Higher Unemployment -- t3. The Contention that Countries Can't Compete if They Protect Working Adults -- t4. The Myth that Labor Laws Do Not Make a Difference -- t5. Achieving Global Consensus -- t6. Addressing Where the World Lags Behind -- t7. Moving from Evidence to Action: Raising the Floor of Working Conditions and Equity -- tAppendix -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNews stories on the impact of job loss appear daily in the media. Less reported is that working conditions in many countries around the world have deteriorated as rapidly as jobs have been lost-and this affects ten times as many people. Working conditions significantly impact our health, the amount of time we can spend with family, our options during momentous life events (such as the birth of a child or the death of a parent), and whether we keep or lose a job when the unexpected occurs. Inexplicably, the global community has nearly universally accepted the argument that any country that guarantees a floor of decent working conditions will suffer higher unemployment and will be less competitive. Raising the Global Floor shatters this widely held view by presenting the first ever, global analysis of the relationship between labor conditions, national competitiveness, and unemployment rates in 190 countries. The authors' findings are dramatic. They show that there is no relationship between unemployment rates and providing basic protections in a series of critical areas. Strikingly, data also indicate that good working conditions can make countries more competitive. There are no long-term economic gains to be had if workers are denied paid sick leave, paid annual leave, paid parental leave, the right to a day of rest, and many other basic protections that would improve the quality of their lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEmployee rights. 0aLabor economics. 0aLabor laws and legislation. 0aLabor policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aEarle, Alison, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477253240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804772532423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804772532.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles